why: If equal harm was caused, I rated them equally unless there was a substantial mitigating circumstance. For instance, due to the exchange rates, a police officer holding people hostage for $100 in Mexico is actually asking for *more money* relative to what he/she could be expected to buy than a police officer in Spain asking for the same flat amount. Likewise, a US marine accidentally shooting a comrade in a war zone is more understandable than in a training exercise (more on edge, more potential rationale for being too trigger happy).

I either looked at which action caused more harm or which action caused a place that normally seems safe to feel unsafe. For example, for the choice between a child setting a doll and cat on fire, I chose setting the cat on fire because it harms something living. For the choice between terrorists bombing a bus in Israel or London, I chose London because London usually feels safe from this type of attack, and the feeling of insecurity that comes with an attack in a normally safe place makes it worse.
Because it was my opinion about this topics

In the questions that involved weapons, I based some of the judgment on the type of weapon. On some of the other questions, like the rape question, i based the judgment on whether or not there could be anticipation of a potentially bad situation. Going to a bar would cause a prudent person to keep an eye on their drink but in a coffee shop that presumption of intoxication is absent. Situations definitely made a difference in my choices but locations, like certain states/cities, weren't as significant.
thoughts: very interesting and different from the usual, thanks very much!

Most of the time, both situations appeared equally bad. Occasionally, with regards to where the crime was committed, it seemed that the location that I would least expect such an atrocity to occur I viewed as worse.

I thought about which action brought the most harm. In the case of spoiled food at a 4 star restaurant and the police officer being killed while investigating vandalism, I labeled those as worse because people going into those situations had less reason to expect this, and therefore were probably more adversely affected.

Most of the actions were not worse than the other, in my opinion. In my thoughts, there are absolutes: for example, rape is rape whether committed by a barista or a bartender. In a few cases the people can expect a better quality of behavior (4-star restaurant vs fast food). But, for the most part people, companies, organizations should act morally and ethically.
thoughts: One of the more interesting surveys. Thank you.
